This document mainly contains Chinese news reports on COVID-19 released at the beginning of the outbreak (from December 1 to January 31). Some of these were published by Chinese news media and local Chinese governments. These news articles provide reliable clues to the Chinese government's possible intention to silence and cover up the epidemic. Many articles were later deleted from the Internet, but a group of interested people have saved them on GitHub. They organize the archives into a timeline with the purpose of "preserving" history so that the truth will not be hidden or forgotten over time. The original timeline is in Chinese. This is an English translation so that Western readers can also learn the truth behind the Covid-19 outbreak.

Documentary of COVID-19 Outbreak: Timeline

This is a translated document. The original document is in (Chinese):

December 1, 2019

·       The first Wuhan resident had symptoms of unexplained pneumonia (Diagnosed afterwards, it was unknow pneumonia of unknown cause at the time and no doctor found and reported). According to Wu Wenxuan, director of the intensive care unit (ICU) of Jinyintan Hospital, the patient was a man in his 70s with a bit of a cerebral infarction and Alzheimer's disease. After became ill, he was admitted to another hospital in Wuhan, but as his condition worsened, he was transferred to Jinyintan Hospital on December 29. The old man lived four or five stops (bus stop) away from the seafood market, because he had been ill at home, basically did not go out, and did not go to the South China seafood market. The onset of the disease on December 1st was based on epidemiological investigations combining family memories. See Chaolin Huang, et al. Clinical features of patients infected with 2019 novel coronavirus in Wuhan, China. The Lancet, Jan. 24, 2020 (Clinical characteristics of new coronavirus infections in Wuhan, China, 2019) and BBC Chinese| pneumonia outbreak: Vague detection of patients with zero detection and disputes over the source of the virus.

 

【Note: pay attention to the emergence of illness, hospital admission, diagnosis of unexplained (viral) pneumonia, diagnosis of xinguan pneumonia, determine the limited human transmission, determine the difference between continuous human transmission. This timeline focuses on the recording of information (concept) time.  】

 

December 4, 2019

·       The Hubei CDC held the 2019 training course on the maintenance and geoanalysis of direct reporting codes in the province from December 4 to 7, with the participation of the heads of departments responsible for the reporting and management of infectious disease outbreaks in 17 cities and counties in the province and the business personnel responsible for standard coding maintenance. The meeting was chaired by Huang Shuqiong, Director of the Disease Surveillance Department of the Information Institute, and attended the opening ceremony by Huang Xibao, Vice President of the Provincial CDC, Li Mingyan, Director of the Information Institute, and Vice Director Liu Kehao. President Huang put forward three points of view: First, to determine the achievements, carefully summarize, to ensure the comprehensive quality of infectious disease information the first good results in the country. Second, to attach great importance to clear requirements to ensure that the annual code maintenance work is completed on time with quality and quantity. Third, to seize the opportunity and actively make breakthroughs to ensure that disease surveillance big data plays a role in disease prevention and control.

The standard, the "Standard for the Entry and Exclusion of Unexplained Viral Pneumonia" in the Manual of Medical Treatment of Unexplained Viral Pneumonia (White Cover), stipulates that the conditions for the inclusion of cases of unexplained viral pneumonia must be consistent with both epidemiological history (History of Exposure to South China Seafood Market and its Associated Personnel) and four clinical manifestations (1. Fever  ≥38 degrees C, 2. Imaging characteristics of pneumonia, 3. The total number of white blood cells in the early stages of onset is normal or decreased, or the lymphocyte count is reduced, 4. The condition has not improved or worsened after 3 days of standardized antimicrobial medication), and cannot be clearly diagnosed with other diseases. The doctors interviewed believed that the White Skin Manual's "Intake Standard" was too demanding and unfavorable for early detection and early diagnosis. In addition, the white skin manual also includes Cao Bin's "Unexplained Viral Pneumonia Treatment Program (Trial)," which defines cases as meeting four clinical criteria (similar to the "Entry Criteria") or meeting the first three standards plus epidemiological standards (patients with exposure history of the South China Seafood Market in Wuhan City or similar patient exposure history), while not being able to clearly diagnose pneumonia cases for other diseases (see Article 1 of January). The first members of the national health care commission's expert group said that the "diagnosis and treatment plan" was developed by them around January 3 in conjunction with the local expert group in Hubei Province, but they were not involved in the development of the "entry criteria" and were informed of the document afterwards. According to media reports, what the Group was aware of at the time was a green-covered WorkBook, the difference between the two covers was whether or not to include the Entry Criteria. It has also been reported that members of the national and provincial expert groups saw the white cover of the "work manual", asked the Wuhan Health and Wellness Commission to withdraw and reprint the manual while removing the "entry standards" after the green cover "work manual", but the hospitals implemented the diagnostic and reporting standards have not changed, until the National Health Commission issued the first edition of the "New Coronary Pneumonia Treatment Program."  See February 20 Ice Point Weekly| White And Green Manual: ChangeS In The Diagnostic CriteriA For Coronavirus And FebruarY 24 Caixin.Com | Wuhan Fire Line Rescue 50 Days Of On-Site Records.

The full name of the infectious disease report card is “The Infectious Disease Report Card of the People's Republic of China”. According to the “Regulations on the Management of Infectious Disease Information Reporting” (2015 Edition), first-time doctors who discover infectious disease patients, suspected patients and prescribed reported pathogen carriers during diagnosis and treatment shall fill out the Infectious Disease Report Card as required or automatically extract an electronic infectious disease report card that meets the criteria for the exchange of documents through electronic medical records and electronic health files... Other outbreaks, epidemics or unexplained infectious diseases should also be reported on the Infectious Diseases Report Card. As long as the hospital reports an infectious disease report card, the district (county), city, province, and national CDC to which the hospital belongs can receive information in real time. In the three days from January 8 to 10, the hospital reported 9, 4 and 1 "unexplained pneumonia" report cards. ·       The New England Journal of Medicine published a paper, "The Early Transmission Dynamics of Pneumonia with New Coronary Virus Infection in Wuhan, China",    The corresponding authors are Feng Zijian, deputy director of the China Center for Disease Control and Prevention, Yang Bo, director of the Hubei Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention, and Gao Fu, director of the China Center for Disease Control and Prevention, are co-authors. Based on the analysis of 425 confirmed cases (including 15 medical staff) reported as of January 23, 2020, the paper concluded that there were clear characteristics of human-to-human transmission at the end of December. Based on retrospective analysis, all cases have been announced to the public before the paper was written. The viewpoint that “person-to-person transmission occurred among close contacts in December 2019” put forward in the paper is a retrospective inference based on the epidemiological survey data of 425 cases.
